The HD 205739 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 205739 is a star with 1.22 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.33 times its radius. It is located 302.48 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 2.84 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HD 205739 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 205739 system


HD 205739 b

HD 205739 b was discovered by the Las Campanas Observatory observatory using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 0.90 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 205739 b is 435.66 times the mass of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 205739 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
